{{about|the astronomical object|the Swans album|The Great Annihilator}} {{Starbox short | name = Great Annihilator | constell = [[Ophiuchus (constellation)|Ophiuchus]] | ra = {{RA|17|43|54.83}}<ref name=SIMBAD>{{cite simbad|title=NAME Great Annihilator}}</ref> | dec = {{DEC|-29|44|42.6}}<ref name=SIMBAD/> | class = [[Red giant]] + [[Black hole]]<ref>{{cite journal|title=Orbital and Superorbital Periods of 1E 1740.7-2942 and GRS 1758-258|author1=Smith, D. M.|date=2002|journal=The Astrophysical Journal|volume=578|issue=2|doi=10.1086/344701|arxiv=astro-ph/0209255|bibcode=2002ApJ...578L.129S }}</ref> | Simbad = NAME+Great+Annihilator }} '''1E1740.7-2942''', or the '''Great Annihilator''',<ref>{{cite journal | last1=Sunyaev | first1=R. A. | authorlink1=Rashid Sunyaev | last2=Borozdin | first2=K. N. | last3=Aleksandrovich | first3=N. L. | last4=Arefev | first4=V. A. | last5=Kaniovskii | first5=A. S. | last6=Efremov | first6=V. V. | last7=Maisack | first7=M. | last8=Reppin | first8=C. | last9=Skinner | first9=J. K. | title=Observations of X-ray novae in Vela (1993), Ophiuchus (1993), and Perseus (1992) using the instruments of the Mir-Kvant module | journal=Astronomy Letters | date=November 1994 | volume=20 | issue=6 | page=777 | bibcode=1994AstL...20..777S }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Odenwald | first1=Sten | authorlink1=Sten Odenwald | title=What do we know about the 'Great Annihilator' in the center of the Milky Way? | url=http://www.astronomycafe.net/qadir/q1632.html | website=Astronomy Cafe | accessdate=4 August 2014 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116203353/http://www.astronomycafe.net/qadir/q1632.html | archivedate=16 January 2013 | date=1997}}</ref> is a large [[black hole]] thought to be located in the core region of the [[Milky Way]], near the supermassive black hole [[Sagittarius A*|Sgr A*]] at the [[Galactic Center]].<ref>{{cite web | title=The Great Annihilator in the Central Region of the Galaxy | last1=Mirabel | first1=I. F. | url=https://www.eso.org/sci/publications/messenger/archive/no.70-dec92/messenger-no70-51-54.pdf | publisher=eso.org | pages=51–54}}</ref> It is one of the brightest [[gamma ray]] sources found in the Milky Way, producing massive amounts of [[photon]] pairs at 511 keV, which usually indicates the annihilation of an electron-positron pair. The Great Annihilator also has a radio source counterpart that emits jets approximately three light-years long. These jets are probably synchrotron emissions from [[Pair production|positron-electron pairs]] streaming out at high velocities from the source of antimatter.
