{{Infobox scientist | name = Mahala Andrews | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = 1939 | birth_place = | death_date = 1997 | death_place = | nationality = [[British people|British]] | other_names = | fields = [[Vertebrate paleontology]] | alma_mater = [[University of Cambridge]] | work_institutions = [[National Museum of Scotland]] | occupation = [[paleontologist]] | doctoral_students = | notable_students = }} '''Mahala Andrews''' was a [[palaeontology|palaeontologist]] who worked for the [[National Museum of Scotland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aap.gsa.org.au/files/NomenNudum28.pdf|title=Campbell, K. S. W. and Barwick, R. E.|work=Nomen Nudum|publisher=Association of Australasian Palaeontologists|accessdate=14 March 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110822232351/http://aap.gsa.org.au/files/NomenNudum28.pdf|archivedate=22 August 2011|df=}}</ref> During her career, Andrews wrote many studies on the [[prehistoric]] [[lobe-finned fish]] ''[[Onychodus]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Andrewsa1|first=Mahala|author2=John Long |author3=Per Ahlberg |author4=Richard Barwick |author5=Ken Campbell |date=September 2005|title=The structure of the sarcopterygian Onychodus jandemarrai n. sp. from Gogo, Western Australia: with a functional interpretation of the skeleton|journal=Earth and Environmental Science Transactions of the Royal Society of Edinburgh|volume=96 |pages=197–307 |url=http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayAbstract?fromPage=online&aid=1199892|doi=10.1017/s0263593305000106}}</ref> She was a [[Christian]] and died on the Scottish island of [[Iona]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/dr-mahala-andrews-1.364512|title=Dr Mahala Andrews|website=HeraldScotland}}</ref>
